d English  <i>Lēofsunu</i>).","2  Scottish:  see  Livingstone  .","3  Jewish:  see  Levison  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Levison","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from   Levy  .","English: variant of <b>Leveson</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Leveson</i>, <i>Loveson</i> (Old English <i>Lēofsunu</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>sunu</i> ‘son’).","Scottish: variant of   Livingston  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"Leverson","meanings":["Altered form of Jewish   Levison   or   Levinson  .","English: variant of <b>Leveson</b> (see   Levison  )."]},{"name":"Lowson","meanings":["1  English, Scottish: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Low</i>, a pet form of  <i>Laurence</i> (  see  Lawrence  ) +  <i>-son</i>.  Compare  Lawson  ,   Larson  , and   Lorrison  .","2  English, Scottish:  see  Leveson  ."]},{"name":"Livingstone","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Livingston  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":20,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Leveson was born in 1362, in Willenhall, Staffordshire, England, his father, John Leveson II, was 23 and his mother, Agnes Botetourt, was 14. He married Joanna DeRushall in 1404, in Ellastone, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1409, in Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1362–1409":"1362–1409","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1385–1459":"1385–1459","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1404":"1404","1459":"1459","1348":"1348","1388":"1388","1385":"1385","1362":"1362","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","13